node.text:
This video is from the brilliantly minded Dr Russ Harris, he's a really big name in a therapy called acceptance and commitment therapy, which I can shamelessly say I'm obsessed with. (It works wonders for me and my clients experiencing anxiety, depression, long term health conditions and a bunch more ). So our brains 🧠 have evolved to think negatively in order to keep us safe and alive, that was really really really necessary 1000s of years ago when we were being chased by sabre tooth tigers and stuff, but now... Not so much. Sometimes we think negatively, then get down on ourselves for thinking negatively, making us think even more negatively, You see where I'm going with this ♻️. We need to remember that it's not necessarily our fault that we do this BUT we can decide whether or not we want to continue to do it.

I hope this vid was helpful in explaining how we got here!

Stay tuned for more info tips and tricks ❤️❤️ #motivationmondays

node.text:
Allow me to reintroduce myself my name is...⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Dr Michaela Dunbar ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Chartered Clinical Psychologist and Founder of ‘MyEasyTherapy’. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
I've had 10,000s of new followers in the last few months that are probably like, "ok but who the hell is she?" lol. I'm a force of nature ladies that's coming to change your life muahahhaha.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
If I'm not in my clinic delivering a therapy or coaching session (on zoom, cheers covid) you can find me driving through London rapping along to 2Pac (I’m old school) on my way to barre class - like ballet but for those of us that hate the gym and want to do something more fun to get toned.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
I’m that kind of Psychologist…⁠⁠
⁠⁠
The kind you've probably never met before. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
But don’t let my penchant for 90s rap music fool you. I can get you unstuck and out of your slump in a couple of months. (I have receipts). ⁠
⁠⁠
Growing up I didn't have access to a basic understanding of mental health, for example, what exactly is anxiety and how do we manage difficult emotions? ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
A lot of the struggles I had with social anxiety probably could have been prevented if I knew just how it worked. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Working in the field of mental health for over 10 years I can see that not much has changed for the people of today, and the number of children and adults struggling with mental health conditions is a reflection of this.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
So why My Easy Therapy? ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Well going back to the lack of basic understanding about mental health and emotions - I believe there’s no reason why it has to stay that way. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
'My Easy Therapy' bridges the gap between complex psychological concepts (usually reserved for people that have the money to access therapy), and everyday women like me and you.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
How? ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
By delivering invaluable mental health-related information and intervention in an easily accessible way. Whether that be through 1:1 work, online courses, or brilliant forums like this. ⁠
⁠
Oh, and did I tell you I’m writing a book? If you struggle with anxiety, overthinking, over functioning and people pleasing then click the LINK IN BIO to pre-or⁠der now!

node.text:
BREAKING NEWS ***MAJOR LIFE UPDATE***⁠
⁠
I’m so excited to share with you that I’m writing a book! ⁠
⁠
You’ve Got This is my go-to guide for overcoming self-doubt, taking control of anxiety, and unlocking your full potential. ⁠
⁠
Filled with all the insight, tools and advice that I’ve learned over the years as a clinical psychologist (that I wish I had), I’ll show you how to tackle everything that’s holding you back - from people pleasing to imposter syndrome - so you can step confidently into a life you love.⁠
⁠
You’ve Got This will be published by @michaeljbooks @penguinukbooks on 28th April 2022 and you can pre-order it now via the link in my bio!’⁠
⁠
I need you all to know that it wouldn't have been possible without you, your love and support means everything. ⁠
⁠
I spent ALOT of time feeling as though I wasn’t as competent or intelligent as others might think—and that soon enough, people would discover the ‘truth’ about me. ⁠
⁠
I managed to gain a place on clinical training and complete a doctorate but I still felt like a fraud. Instead of acknowledging my capabilities and my efforts I put it all down to luck and good timing. ⁠
⁠
I felt pressure to perform at my absolute best 100 percent of the time, and when I didn't, I felt incompetent and anxious. ⁠
⁠
Growing up I didn't know I had anxiety. I just knew that when I was in a group my heart would race, and my brain told me 'if you speak, you're going to say something ridiculous, and people will think you're ridiculous".⁠
⁠
BUT what does a girl with anxiety that doesn’t know she has anxiety do?⁠
⁠
She trains for 6 years to become a psychologist to help other people get rid of their anxiety and ends up helping 1000s of people overcome their anxiety and step into a life they can truly love. ⁠
⁠
Then she forces herself to face the things she’s scared of and learns that with or without anxiety (and all the above) she is actually powerful. ⁠
⁠
For me, having the opportunity to write this book for all the women experience the same things I did and help them step into their power makes it all worth it. ⁠
⁠
Thankyou ❤️ ⁠
⁠
P.S Get those pre-orders in please I'm trying to make this a bestseller baby 🎉🎉🎉LINK IN BIO

node.text:
Procrastination = low self esteem…harsh right? This isn’t the case in every single situation sometimes we just don’t want to do ‘the thing’ to avoid feeling bored or tired etc but for many low self esteem has a lot to answer for. Who can relate? 

Ok, so you have a task to do and you're feeling tempted to procrastinate? Now what?⁠
⁠⁠
Try this...⁠⁠
⁠⁠
1. Bring attention to your thoughts: What's the story in your mind. What is your brain telling you. "I'm going to fail at this. I won't do a good job. It will take too long. I'm going to be sooo bored doing it. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Ask yourself - can I have these thoughts and still get the work done.? The answer is usually always YES.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
2. Bring your attention to the sensations in your body. What feelings are triggering your temptation to procrastinate? Anxiety, sadness, boredom. Where do you feel them in your body? What do they remind you of? ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Ask yourself. Can I have these feelings and still get the work done.? The answer is usually always YES.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
3. Consider the next action: At the start of a given task, you can consider the next action as just a possibility, as if you were  acting: “What’s the next action I’d take on this if I were going to do it, even though I’m not?” Maybe you would open your email. Or perhaps you would put the date at the top of your document. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
4. Do the'next action'. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
5. BE NICE show self-compassion🤗: Treat yourself with kindness and understanding in the face of your mistakes, forgive yourself in the moments you procrastinate.⁠ There's no point being mean to yourself, it will just keep your threat response activated, maintaining the uncomfortable feelings associated with the task. ⁠⁠

If you're looking at this post scratching your head like how did she know 👀Then get yourself on the waitlist for my upcoming therapeutic group coaching programme Frozen to Fearless. ⁠⁠LINK IN BIO
⁠
P.S ⁠ I’ve got a ridiculously exciting life update to share with you tomorrow so keep your eyes peeled for my IG live at 1pm where I’ll be sharing Errryyyythang

node.text:
Why Emotional Intelligence Was The Key To My Success 
⁠
Ok so in a nutshell emotional intelligence is the ability to identify, understand and manage our own emotions and the emotions of others. Experts agree that this particular type of intelligence plays a vital role in success, and some have suggested that emotional intelligence may be more important than IQ. Wild right?⁠
⁠
At a personal level, emotional intelligence helps you:⁠
⁠
Have those uncomfortable talks without hurting anyone’s feelings⁠
Manage our own emotions when we're stressed and overwhelmed⁠
Improve relationships with the people you care about⁠
⁠
At work, emotional intelligence can help us:⁠
⁠
Resolve conflicts ⁠
Coach and motivate others⁠
Create a culture of collaboration⁠
Build psychological safety within teams⁠
⁠
Unfortunately for me like many people I know I wasn’t taught the basics of emotional intelligence. I wasn’t very self aware, I didn't know how to effectively regulate my emotions, I didn’t know what emotions did what, and most of the time I knew I was feeling ‘something’ but didn't know what to call it...Hello anxiety.⁠
⁠
Our emotions come following whatever thoughts we’re thinking. And when emotions run high, they change the way the brain functions, reducing our ability to think, make decisions, even communicate with other people. Understanding and managing my emotions helped me become more successful in my professional life (I literally wouldn’t have started this page if I didn’t get my emotional intelligence shit together) and relationships. ⁠
⁠
Check out the comments for 5 EI skills and a few ways you can improve them.⁠

Photo by Dr. Michaela  | Psychologist on July 26, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Nawal Mustafa M.A. thebraincoach The tendency to people please is often rooted in codependency. Literature identifies codependency as having high self- sacrifice, the need to control or fix other people's problems, external focusing and repressing one's own feelings/behaviors. Codependency is not a disorder. It is a well-researched psychological concept that leads to unhealthy relationship dynamics and enabling of toxic behaviors. It is important to recognize if we are codependent and tend internalize other people's behaviors/words to a point of self-sm and low self-worth. Awareness is the first step to unlearning these patterns of behaviors and thoughts. Roberts, Lange 2004)'.
